00:28:26.764 --> 00:28:30.041
10^(11) meters.
That's something like 10^(12)

00:28:30.041 --> 00:28:32.806
meters.
So, the Earth moves 10,000

00:28:32.806 --> 00:28:37.839
times further in time than it
moves in space in a year.

00:28:37.839 --> 00:28:42.886
And that means that the Earth's
motion in space-time is almost

00:28:42.886 --> 00:28:47.850
precisely a straight line,
going straight forward in time.

00:28:47.850 --> 00:28:50.009
So, here's time.
Here's, I don't know,

00:28:50.009 --> 00:28:52.838
the X-axis.
And you could imagine that as

00:28:52.838 --> 00:28:54.975
time goes on,
the Earth, you know,

00:28:54.975 --> 00:28:57.826
moves around the Sun.
So its X-axis --so its

00:28:57.826 --> 00:29:00.329
X-coordinate goes back
and back--back and forth.

00:29:00.329 --> 00:29:02.346
Here's the Sun,
which, you know,

00:29:02.346 --> 00:29:05.338
wiggles a little bit,
much less than the Earth,

00:29:05.338 --> 00:29:08.093
as we discussed.
But this picture,

00:29:08.093 --> 00:29:12.284
here, is inaccurate,
because in fact this distance

00:29:12.284 --> 00:29:17.299
here, which is half a year,
is 10,000 times longer than

00:29:17.299 --> 00:29:21.289
this distance here,
which is half an orbit.

00:29:21.289 --> 00:29:24.226
And so--and so,
in fact, the Earth's motion is

00:29:24.226 --> 00:29:27.881
represented by something that's
almost exactly a straight

00:29:27.881 --> 00:29:31.861
line--so much so that I couldn't
possibly draw the wiggle in a

00:29:31.861 --> 00:29:35.618
way that you could see it.
So, here's the Earth going

00:29:35.618 --> 00:29:38.460
forward in time.
And the wiggle is really small.

00:29:38.460 --> 00:29:42.605
That's not surprising,
because the gravitational force

00:29:42.605 --> 00:29:46.829
of the Sun is small enough so
that the Earth's orbit is

00:29:46.829 --> 00:29:50.349
correctly described by Newtonian
physics.

00:29:50.349 --> 00:29:55.367
And so, this is one of those
situations where you have a

00:29:55.367 --> 00:30:00.750
Newtonian physics in relatively
low gravitational fields.

00:30:00.750 --> 00:30:03.232
And as the gravitational fields
get stronger,

00:30:03.232 --> 00:30:05.319
weird relativistic effects kick
in.

00:30:05.319 --> 00:30:06.740
But that doesn't happen for the
Earth.

00:30:06.740 --> 00:30:13.873
So there's--the number is this.
Schwarzschild radius divided by

00:30:13.873 --> 00:30:20.839
distance, is the measure of how
relativistic an orbit is.

00:30:20.839 --> 00:30:27.480
And if this number is small,
then you get correct answers

00:30:27.480 --> 00:30:33.009
from the Newtonian theory.
And we can work it out.

00:30:33.009 --> 00:30:36.220
The Schwarzschild radius of the
Sun, 3 x 10^(3) meters.

00:30:36.220 --> 00:30:40.609
The distance from the Earth to
the Sun, 1.5 x 10^(11) meters.

00:30:40.609 --> 00:30:46.490
That's 2 x 10^(-8) and that's a
small number.

00:30:46.490 --> 00:30:49.220
So, Earth works fine in a
Newtonian sense.

00:30:49.220 --> 00:30:51.128
Yes?
Student: Is that

00:30:51.128 --> 00:30:53.879
R the radius of the orbit
or the radius of the [inaudible]

00:30:53.879 --> 00:30:56.115
Professor Charles
Bailyn: That is the distance

00:30:56.115 --> 00:30:58.694
of the moving object from the
center of the gravitating thing

00:30:58.694 --> 00:31:00.500
that's making the curvature
happen.

00:31:00.500 --> 00:31:02.660
Yeah.
So, yes is the answer.

00:31:02.660 --> 00:31:04.950
It's the radius of the orbit.
Yes?

00:31:04.950 --> 00:31:07.920
Student: Was the theory
of general relativity a theory

00:31:07.920 --> 00:31:10.396
that was just promulgated,
or does it actually have

00:31:10.396 --> 00:31:12.529
equations associated with it?
Professor Charles

00:31:12.529 --> 00:31:13.957
Bailyn: Oh yes.
Does it have equations

00:31:13.957 --> 00:31:15.630
associated with it?
You bet.

00:31:15.630 --> 00:31:19.769
You don't want to see them.
There's a branch of mathematics

00:31:19.769 --> 00:31:23.096
called differential geometry,
because--what happens is,

00:31:23.096 --> 00:31:25.559
this curvature stuff is all
geometry.

00:31:25.559 --> 00:31:29.023
And the problem is that the
further away you get from an

00:31:29.023 --> 00:31:31.480
object, the less the space is
curved.

00:31:31.480 --> 00:31:34.271
So, the amount on the sphere,
on the surface of the

00:31:34.271 --> 00:31:36.839
sphere--it's curved the same way
everywhere.

00:31:36.839 --> 00:31:39.782
So, the equations that describe
the curvature are the same at

00:31:39.782 --> 00:31:42.572
any point on a sphere.
But you can imagine something

00:31:42.572 --> 00:31:45.519
that starts out with strong
curvature and tails off.

00:31:45.519 --> 00:31:47.941
And then the amount of
curvature at any given point is

00:31:47.941 --> 00:31:50.936
different from any other point.
So, you have to describe it

00:31:50.936 --> 00:31:54.128
with a differential amount of
curvature, and then integrate

00:31:54.128 --> 00:31:57.168
over the path that things take.
This gets heinous,

00:31:57.168 --> 00:31:59.309
and we're not going to go
there.

00:31:59.309 --> 00:32:02.170
But I will show you,
next time, some specific

00:32:02.170 --> 00:32:04.640
examples of some of these
equations,

00:32:04.640 --> 00:32:07.610
because it'll help explain
things like why space and time

00:32:07.610 --> 00:32:10.210
are reversed inside an event
horizon and stuff.

00:32:10.210 --> 00:32:11.956
But, you bet,
there's a whole mathematical

00:32:11.956 --> 00:32:13.989
theory.
In fact, Einstein was not the

00:32:13.989 --> 00:32:17.344
world's greatest mathematician
and it took him until 1917 to

00:32:17.344 --> 00:32:20.180
get all this worked out.
He had to go and get himself

00:32:20.180 --> 00:32:22.828
some math tutoring at the
University of Göttingen and--so

00:32:22.828 --> 00:32:25.289
that he could understand the
geometric properties.

00:32:25.289 --> 00:32:28.220
So, yeah, there's a big
mathematical theory behind it.

00:32:28.220 --> 00:32:30.341
Yes?
Student: So,

00:32:30.341 --> 00:32:33.980
if gravity is not a force,
how can you use F = ma?

00:32:33.980 --> 00:32:37.612
Professor Charles
Bailyn: F = ma is a

00:32:37.612 --> 00:32:41.817
general equation of motion.
It doesn't have to be the force

00:32:41.817 --> 00:32:44.049
of gravity.
There are many other forces in

00:32:44.049 --> 00:32:45.797
the world.
Student: But when you're

00:32:45.797 --> 00:32:47.737
setting F = ma to
GMM or [inaudible]

00:32:47.737 --> 00:32:49.400
Professor Charles
Bailyn: Right,

00:32:49.400 --> 00:32:52.602
so, that's the Newtonian idea,
that you set F = ma

00:32:52.602 --> 00:32:54.890
equal to GMM over
D^(2).

00:32:54.890 --> 00:32:59.272
And the thing that prompted
Einstein's thought was the fact

00:32:59.272 --> 00:33:03.579
that the two different kinds of
masses on each side of the

00:33:03.579 --> 00:33:07.881
equation turned out to be equal.
And you can see why this

00:33:07.881 --> 00:33:10.801
explains that.
Because, if what's happening is

00:33:10.801 --> 00:33:13.605
that you curve space,
and then things follow a

00:33:13.605 --> 00:33:16.970
trajectory dictated by the
curvature of that space,

00:33:16.970 --> 00:33:20.130
then it makes perfect sense
that all objects follow the same

00:33:20.130 --> 00:33:22.220
trajectory, regardless of their
mass.

00:33:22.220 --> 00:33:25.990
Because they're not actually
being forced to move anywhere.

00:33:25.990 --> 00:33:28.470
They're just going in straight
lines, and straight lines are

00:33:28.470 --> 00:33:30.109
the same no matter what your
mass is.

00:33:30.109 --> 00:33:33.701
And so, that's why this kind of
curvature provides an

00:33:33.701 --> 00:33:37.500
explanation for what,
in the Newtonian approximation,

00:33:37.500 --> 00:33:43.960
is the equality of the inertial
and the gravitational mass.

